            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How the German VAT (Umsatzsteuer) calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool helps you quickly calculate German VAT at the standard
                rate of <strong>19%</strong> and the reduced rate of
                <strong>7%</strong>. You can:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Convert <strong>net to gross</strong> (add VAT).</li>
                <li>Convert <strong>gross to net</strong> (extract VAT).</li>
                <li>
                  Build an <strong>invoice with mixed VAT rates</strong> and see
                  totals per rate.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">From net to gross</p>
                <p>
                  Let \( r \) be the VAT rate (e.g. 19% → 0.19) and \( N \) the
                  net amount.
                </p>
                <p>\[ \text{VAT} = N \times r \]</p>
                <p>\[ \text{Gross} = N \times (1 + r) \]</p>
                <hr class="my-3" />
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">From gross to net</p>
                <p>Let \( G \) be the gross amount.</p>
                <p>\[ \text{Net} = \frac{G}{1 + r} \]</p>
                <p>\[ \text{VAT} = G - \text{Net} \]</p>
              </div>

              <h2>German VAT rates at a glance</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Standard rate 19%</strong> – applies to most goods and
                  services.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Reduced rate 7%</strong> – applies to many basic goods
                  and cultural services (e.g. most food, books, newspapers,
                  local public transport).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>0% / exempt</strong> – exports, intra-EU supplies and
                  certain financial, medical and educational services can be
                  zero-rated or exempt.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                VAT rules change over time (for example, temporary rate
                reductions were introduced during the COVID-19 pandemic). Always
                check the latest guidance from the German tax authorities or a
                professional advisor for complex or high-value transactions.
              </p>

              <h3>Example: 19% VAT</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Net price: €100.00</li>
                <li>VAT (19%): €100 × 0.19 = €19.00</li>
                <li>Gross price: €100 × 1.19 = €119.00</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Example: 7% VAT</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Net price: €100.00</li>
                <li>VAT (7%): €100 × 0.07 = €7.00</li>
                <li>Gross price: €100 × 1.07 = €107.00</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Typical use cases</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Freelancers and small businesses</strong> preparing
                  German invoices.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Online sellers</strong> displaying prices with and
                  without VAT.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Accountants and bookkeepers</strong> checking VAT
                  breakdowns.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consumers</strong> understanding how much VAT is
                  included in a price.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on arithmetic for German VAT amounts. It
                does not:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Validate German VAT IDs (USt-IdNr.).</li>
                <li>
                  Determine place-of-supply rules for cross-border services.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Handle special schemes (e.g. margin scheme, small business
                  exemption &ldquo;Kleinunternehmerregelung&rdquo;).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For compliance questions, filing obligations or complex
                scenarios, consult a qualified tax advisor or the German tax
                authorities (Finanzamt). This tool is for informational and
                planning purposes only and does not constitute tax advice.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What are the current German VAT rates?</h3>
              <p>
                The standard VAT rate is <strong>19%</strong>. A reduced rate of
                <strong>7%</strong> applies to many essential goods and services
                such as most groceries, books, newspapers and local public
                transport. Some supplies are zero-rated or exempt, including
                exports, intra-EU supplies and certain financial and medical
                services.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I calculate VAT from a gross price?</h3>
              <p>
                Divide the gross price by <code>1 + rate</code> to get the net
                price, then subtract. For example, with 19% VAT:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Net = Gross ÷ 1.19</li>
                <li>VAT = Gross − Net</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Can I use this for VAT refunds on purchases in Germany?</h3>
              <p>
                You can use the calculator to estimate the VAT portion of a
                purchase, but eligibility and procedures for VAT refunds (for
                example, for non-EU tourists) are governed by specific legal
                rules. Always follow the official refund process and
                documentation requirements.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator check if a German VAT ID is valid?</h3>
              <p>
                No. To check a German VAT ID (USt-IdNr.), use the official EU
                VIES VAT number validation service or the tools provided by the
                German tax authorities.
              </p>
